You are a researcher. In order to carry out your research, you first carried out a literature search, the following is an experimental protocol organized from a relevant piece of literature you obtained from your search. Read each part of the experimental protocol carefully and analyze whether you can refer to that section in your research in the context of the purpose and conditions of your research, giving a referability rating (low, medium, or high) for each part and explaining why; and giving suggestions for references (eg. what methods you can learn from it and what datasets mentioned in the protocol can be used for your research) and modifications (eg. what should be changed for fit your research) to fit your research. 

Protocol:Experiment
Classification of the Immune Microenvironment and Identification of Key Genes in Liposarcoma Based on Transcriptomics

Here is your research objective:Available Resources: Frozen samples, sarcoma cell lines, and paraffin sections. Data Sources: RNA sequencing data from 80 cases and single-cell sequencing data from 10 cases, along with any publicly available datasets. Animal Experiments: All necessary materials are available if required. Funding: The total funding for the experiment is 200,000 RMB. Computing Resources: Sufficient computing resources are accessible for data analysis. 
Your research conditions are as follows:null. 
The mandatory requirements you must fulfill in your experimental design are listed below: <ArticleTitle>Comprehensive Analysis of a Six-Gene Signature Predicting Survival and Immune Infiltration of Liposarcoma Patients and Deciphering Its Therapeutic Significance.</ArticleTitle>: 

{
    "Future Directions": "Future Research Directions",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Explore Additional Molecular Targets for Treatment\n\u2460 Conduct a comprehensive literature review to identify potential molecular targets related to liposarcoma, focusing on genes that have shown promise in previous studies, such as MDM2 and CDK4. \n\u2461 Utilize bioinformatics tools, such as gene expression profiling and pathway analysis software (e.g., GSEA, KEGG), to analyze existing datasets from the Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO), specifically GSE21122 and GSE159659, to identify new therapeutic targets. \n\u2462 Design and perform in vitro experiments using liposarcoma cell lines, such as LPS141 and LPS-1, to evaluate the efficacy of novel drugs targeting these identified molecular pathways. For example, testing the effects of MDM2 inhibitors in these cell lines could yield promising results.\n\u2463 Implement in vivo studies in appropriate animal models (e.g., xenograft models) to assess the therapeutic potential and safety of these drugs before proceeding to clinical trials. Monitor tumor growth and metastasis using imaging techniques and histological analysis.",
        "original text": "the pathogenesis of LPS has not been well-elucidated yet. So far, oncogenes, including MDM2, CDK4 and HMGA2, as well as signaling pathways, including MAPK, erbB, JAK-STAT and Wnt, may play major roles in tumorigenesis.",
        "results": "A six-gene signature was developed to predict distant recurrence-free survival (DRFS) of LPS patients and showed higher precision performance in more aggressive LPS subtypes.",
        "results original text": "The prognosis of LPS varies according to its subtype classification: WDLPS or low-grade MLPS patients exhibit a higher five-year survival rate of up to 90%; conversely, that of DDLPS or PLPS could be as low as 30%."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Investigate Mechanisms of Tumor Resistance\n\u2460 Analyze patient samples from clinical trials who have shown resistance to current therapies to identify common genetic mutations or expression patterns associated with resistance, focusing on genes involved in drug metabolism and repair mechanisms. \n\u2461 Utilize animal models (e.g., nude mice with implanted tumors) to study the tumor microenvironment and determine how it contributes to therapeutic resistance, particularly focusing on immune evasion and metabolic adaptations. \n\u2462 Develop combination therapy strategies that could potentially overcome resistance mechanisms, including using checkpoint inhibitors (e.g., anti-PD-1) alongside traditional chemotherapy or targeted therapies (e.g., CDK4/6 inhibitors). \n\u2463 Assess the impact of these combinations on tumor growth and progression through longitudinal studies and imaging techniques, and analyze immune cell infiltration using flow cytometry and immunohistochemistry. Previous studies have indicated that combination therapies can enhance treatment efficacy in resistant tumors.",
        "original text": "Currently, chemotherapeutics, including eribulin, doxorubicin and trabectedin, have been proven to be better responses in different LPS subtypes; however, these treatment approaches for advanced LPS patients are limited and unsatisfactory.",
        "results": "The high-risk group was significantly enriched in cell cycle-related pathways. In the LPS microenvironment, neutrophils, memory B cells and resting mast cells exhibited significant differences in cell abundance between high-risk and low-risk patients.",
        "results original text": "A nomogram was further established for clinical application based on this risk model. Via GSEA, the high-risk group was significantly enriched in cell cycle-related pathways."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Assess Long-Term Outcomes of Patients in Clinical Trials\n\u2460 Collect and analyze follow-up data from patients involved in clinical trials evaluating new therapies for liposarcoma, focusing on long-term survival rates, recurrence rates, and quality of life metrics using validated questionnaires. \n\u2461 Perform statistical analyses, including Kaplan-Meier survival analysis and multivariate regression, to determine the long-term outcomes and factors influencing survival in these patients. \n\u2462 Compare outcomes across different liposarcoma subtypes (e.g., DDLPS vs. WDLPS) to assess the efficacy of specific treatments, particularly in high-risk populations. \n\u2463 Utilize patient-reported outcomes and clinical assessments to gain insights into the overall impact of new therapies on patients' lives, correlating these findings with clinical data to identify predictors of success. Insights from these assessments could inform future therapeutic strategies and improve patient management.",
        "original text": "In view of this, it is essential to explore the underlying mechanisms of the pathogenesis of LPS and develop molecular-targeted therapeutic strategies for LPS.",
        "results": "The risk score was significantly correlated with therapeutic targets. Moreover, this model was significantly correlated with therapeutic targets.",
        "results original text": "This model was significantly correlated with therapeutic targets."
    }
}{
    "Part 1": "Identification and Evaluation of Differentially Expressed Genes (DEGs) in Liposarcoma and Normal Adipose Tissues",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Data Normalization and DEG Identification:\n\u2460 Data Download:\n   - Clinical and expression profiling data for liposarcoma (LPS) were obtained from the Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO) database, specifically datasets GSE21122, GSE159659, GSE30929, and GSE159848.\n\u2461 DEG Identification:\n   - The GEO2R analysis tool was used to identify DEGs between LPS and normal adipose tissue samples, applying a false discovery rate (FDR) < 0.05 and |log2 fold change (FC)| \u2265 1 as criteria.\n   - Venn diagrams were generated to illustrate the overlap of DEGs between datasets, ensuring comprehensive coverage of relevant genes for further analysis.\n   - The version of GEO2R used was confirmed to be the latest as of the access date. Examples of DEGs identified include COL5A1 and TOP2A, which were noted for their significant expression changes.",
        "original text": "4.1 Acquisition of Expression Profiling Data and Clinical Information\nFor LPS, clinical and expression profiling data were obtained from the Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/, accessed on 2 March 2022). The gene expression profiles as microarray data were downloaded from the GEO database: GSE21122, GSE159659, GSE30929 and GSE159848 (Table 2). The dataset GSE21122 contains a series of 98 samples, including 89 LPS and 9 normal adipose tissue cases; the dataset GSE159659 includes 30 LPS and 15 normal adipose tissue samples; the dataset GSE30929 is composed of 140 LPS patients with survival data (distant recurrence-free survival, DRFS); the dataset GSE159848 contains 50 LPS patients with survival data (overall survival, OS).",
        "results": "192 common DEGs were identified, including 33 up-regulated and 159 down-regulated genes, which were selected for further analysis.",
        "results original text": "After the normalization of microarray data, DEGs between LPS and normal adipose tissues were identified through GEO2R analysis from two datasets (GSE21122 and GSE159659), respectively. Then, 192 common DEGs overlapped from these two datasets were selected, including 33 up-regulated and 159 down-regulated genes."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Functional Annotation and Pathway Enrichment Analysis:\n\u2460 GO and KEGG Analysis:\n   - The common DEGs were subjected to Gene Ontology (GO) and Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) enrichment analyses using the DAVID online tool.\n   - The analysis focused on biological processes (BP), molecular functions (MF), and cellular components (CC).\n   - Pathways were deemed statistically significant if the FDR < 0.05, with all analyses conducted using the latest version of the DAVID tool available at the time of the study. Examples of significantly enriched pathways include 'negative regulation of cell proliferation' and 'pathways in cancer'.",
        "original text": "4.3 Functional Annotation and Pathway Enrichment Analysis\nTo further discover the underlying biological function of these DEGs, the DAVID online tool (https://david.ncifcrf.gov/) was used to carry out the enrichment analysis of Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) and Gene Ontology (GO), including biological process (BP), molecular function (MF) and cellular component (CC). The p-values were adjusted via the FDR methodology, and a pathway was deemed to be significantly enriched when the FDR < 0.05.",
        "results": "GO analysis showed that enriched functional items were associated with responses to cell growth, including 'negative regulation of cell proliferation' and 'regulation of cell cycle'. KEGG analysis indicated significant enrichment in 'metabolic pathways', 'pathways in cancer', and 'AMPK signaling'.",
        "results original text": "In terms of BP, the enriched functional items were associated with responses to cell growth, including 'negative regulation of cell proliferation' (gene count = 17, p < 0.001) and 'regulation of cell cycle' (gene count = 15, p < 0.001). Additionally, items 'inflammatory response' (gene count = 17, p < 0.001) and 'response to drug' (gene count = 21, p < 0.001) were also functionally enriched. KEGG analysis showed that 'metabolic pathways' (gene count = 39, p < 0.001), 'pathways in cancer' (gene count = 19, p < 0.001) and 'AMPK signaling' (gene count = 13, p < 0.001) were significantly enriched."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. PPI Network and Module Analysis:\n\u2460 PPI Network Construction:\n   - The DEGs were imported into the STRING database to construct a PPI network with a confidence score \u22650.4.\n\u2461 Hub Gene Identification:\n   - The top candidate hub genes were identified using the maximal clique centrality (MCC) algorithm in Cytoscape's plugin Cytohubba.\n\u2462 Module Analysis:\n   - MCODE and ClueGO analyses were performed on the PPI network to identify significant clustering modules and their potential functions, using Cytoscape version 3.8.0. The analyses revealed important modules related to 'platelet-derived growth factor binding' and 'negative regulation of G1/S transition of mitotic cell cycle'.",
        "original text": "4.4 Protein\u2013Protein Interaction Network and Module Analysis\nThe protein\u2013protein interaction (PPI) network is commonly employed to recognize the hub genes involved in the development of disease. The common DEGs were imported into the STRING database (http://string-db.org/), which is an online tool designed to analyze the PPI of genes with a confidence score \u22650.4. Then, the PPI network was constructed and visualized with Cytoscape software (version 3.8.0). Then, the maximal clique centrality (MCC) algorithm in Cytohubba was applied to calculate the hub nodes. Module analysis and GO analysis were subsequently implemented to elucidate the significantly enriched biological function of gene modules through Cytoscape plugins, MCODE and ClueGO.",
        "results": "A PPI network was constructed with significant hub genes identified. The top three clustering modules were related to processes including 'platelet-derived growth factor binding' and 'negative regulation of G1/S transition of mitotic cell cycle'.",
        "results original text": "Furthermore, the PPI network of DEGs was constructed using STRING and Cytoscape with a confidence level of 0.9. The top 25 candidate hub genes were presented in the network. Subsequently, MCODE and ClueGO analyses were conducted to find the significant clustering modules and their potential functions. Then the top three clustering modules were selected, and the network diagram of the pathways was consistent with the corresponding bar charts."
    }
}{
    "Part 2": "Development of a Six-Gene Prognostic Signature by Screening of DRFS-Related DEGs",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Univariate Cox Regression Analysis to Identify DRFS-Related DEGs\n\u2460 Analyze the expression profiling and survival data of 140 patients from the GSE30929 dataset. \n(1) Perform univariate Cox regression analysis to identify DEGs significantly associated with distant recurrence-free survival (DRFS). This analysis should consider factors like age, sex, and treatment history as covariates to ensure reliable results. The statistical significance threshold is set at p < 0.05. (2) Visualize the results to highlight significant DEGs and provide a summary table of the identified DEGs along with their respective hazard ratios and confidence intervals.",
        "original text": "To screen DRFS-related DEGs, Cox regression analysis was performed using expression profiling and survival data of 140 patients from the GSE30929 dataset. According to the univariate Cox regression analysis, 126 DEGs were found to be highly related to DRFS.",
        "results": "A total of 126 DEGs were identified as significantly associated with DRFS through univariate Cox regression analysis.",
        "results original text": "According to the univariate Cox regression analysis, 126 DEGs were found to be highly related to DRFS."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Lasso Cox Regression for Prognostic Model Development Using the glmnet Package\n\u2460 Apply Lasso Cox regression on the identified DEGs.\n(1) Use the glmnet package to construct a prognostic risk model based on the 126 DEGs associated with DRFS. \n(2) Use 10-fold cross-validation to determine the optimal lambda value for the Lasso regression model. (3) Report the final selected significant genes along with their coefficients, ensuring clarity on how these coefficients will be used in the risk score calculations. Include justification for the choice of lambda and its effect on model performance.",
        "original text": "Furthermore, Lasso Cox regression was applied to construct a prognostic risk model based on these 126 DRFS-related DEGs, which consisted of six genes, including Collagen type V alpha 1 chain (COL5A1), DNA topoisomerase II alpha (TOP2A), glycerol-3-phosphate dehydrogenase 1 (GPD1), adrenoceptor beta 2 (ADRB2), G0/G1 switch 2 (G0S2) and adiponectin (ADIPOQ).",
        "results": "The Lasso Cox regression identified a six-gene signature comprising COL5A1, TOP2A, GPD1, ADRB2, G0S2, and ADIPOQ as significant prognostic factors for DRFS.",
        "results original text": "A six-gene signature was developed to predict DRFS of LPS patients and showed higher precision performance in more aggressive LPS subtypes."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Calculation of Risk Score and Patient Stratification Based on the Six-Gene Signature\n\u2460 Calculate the risk score for each patient using the following formula: \nrisk score = expression value of COL5A1*0.037947807 + expression value of TOP2A*0.265638452 + expression value of GPD1*(-0.054047643) + expression value of ADRB2*(-0.148509823) + expression value of G0S2*(-0.006938013) + expression value of ADIPOQ*(-0.014699818).\n\u2461 Stratify patients into high-risk and low-risk groups based on the median risk score. (2) Report the number of patients in each group and how to handle any missing data. (3) Evaluate the prognostic ability of the model through Kaplan-Meier survival analysis and ROC curve analysis, detailing the AUC values for 1-, 3-, and 5-year predictions, and include a brief explanation of how to interpret these results, including what constitutes a clinically significant difference in survival.",
        "original text": "According to the coefficients of Lasso Cox regression, the risk score of this signature can be calculated as follows: risk score = expression value of COL5A1*0.037947807 + expression value of TOP2A*0.265638452 + expression value of GPD1*(-0.054047643) + expression value of ADRB2*(-0.148509823) + expression value of G0S2*(-0.006938013) + expression value of ADIPOQ*(-0.014699818). Then, patients were categorized into two subgroups according to the risk score, defined as the high-risk and low-risk groups.",
        "results": "Patients were stratified into high-risk and low-risk groups based on the median risk score, with significant differences in DRFS observed between these groups. The AUC values for predicting 1-, 3-, and 5-year DRFS were 0.851, 0.850, and 0.788, respectively.",
        "results original text": "Via Kaplan\u2013Meier survival analysis, low-risk patients had significantly better DRFS compared to high-risk patients, with AUC values of 0.851, 0.850, and 0.788 for 1-, 3-, and 5-year predictions."
    }
}{
    "Part 3": "The Expression Features and Prognostic Values of the Six Signature Genes",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Expression Comparison between Tumor and Normal Tissues Using Box and Violin Plots:\n   (1) The expression of the six signature genes (COL5A1, TOP2A, ADRB2, GPD1, G0S2, ADIPOQ) was compared between liposarcoma (LPS) and normal adipose tissue using box plots to visualize differences in expression levels from datasets GSE21122 and GSE159659.\n   (2) Violin plots were utilized to illustrate the distribution of expression levels for each gene from patients in the GSE21122 and GSE159659 datasets, highlighting the differences in expression between tumor and normal tissues.\n   (3) The expression of these genes was also compared between low-risk and high-risk patients based on risk scores calculated from the GSE30929 dataset, using both box plots and violin plots.\n   (4) Statistical analysis was performed using R software (version 4.0.4) with the 'ggplot2' package for visualization.\n   (5) These comparisons aim to establish the differential expression of the genes of interest and assess their potential prognostic value in LPS.",
        "original text": "The expression features of these signature genes were investigated by comparing their expression between tumor and normal tissues (Figure 4). For risk genes, compared to normal tissue, the expression of COL5A1 or TOP2A was significantly higher in LPS; on the contrary, for protective genes, the expression of ADRB2, GPD1, G0S2 or ADIPOQ was significantly higher in normal tissue than that in LPS (Figure 4A,B). Additionally, the expression of risk genes was significantly higher in high-risk LPS patients compared to the low-risk group, while the result of protective genes was the opposite (Figure 4C).",
        "results": "The expression analysis demonstrated that COL5A1 and TOP2A were significantly up-regulated in LPS tissues compared to normal tissues, while ADRB2, GPD1, G0S2, and ADIPOQ were significantly down-regulated in LPS. Furthermore, high-risk LPS patients exhibited significantly higher expression levels of risk genes compared to low-risk patients.",
        "results original text": "For risk genes, compared to normal tissue, the expression of COL5A1 or TOP2A was significantly higher in LPS; on the contrary, for protective genes, the expression of ADRB2, GPD1, G0S2 or ADIPOQ was significantly higher in normal tissue than that in LPS. Additionally, the expression of risk genes was significantly higher in high-risk LPS patients compared to the low-risk group."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Immunohistochemistry Validation of Gene Expression:\n   (1) Multiple immunohistochemistry staining was performed on formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded (FFPE) tissue slices from both normal adipose tissue and LPS samples to validate the expression levels of the signature genes.\n   (2) The primary antibodies used were:\n      - COL5A1: Clone 4A2C7, 1:40, Invitrogen, #18-0223\n      - TOP2A: Clone E29, 1:500, Dako, #M0613\n      - G0S2, GPD1, ADIPOQ, and ADRB2 antibodies were also used as needed.\n   (3) Incubation times for the primary antibodies were set at 1 hour at room temperature, followed by washing steps with PBS.\n   (4) Secondary antibodies were applied according to the manufacturer's instructions.\n   (5) The staining intensity was evaluated using a three-point scale (0 = negative, 1 = weak positive, 2 = strong positive).\n   (6) Results were analyzed using Image J 1.53q software to quantify the fluorescence intensity, comparing LPS and normal tissue expression levels for each gene.\n   (7) Statistical analysis was performed using R software (version 4.0.4) to assess differences in expression levels, reinforcing the findings from previous analyses.",
        "original text": "To verify the expression features of these signature genes, multiple immunohistochemistry staining was performed. Consistent with the above results, the expression of risk genes (COL5A1 and TOP2A) in LPS tissue was significantly higher than that in normal adipose tissue, while the opposite was true for the protective genes, G0S2, GPD1, ADIPOQ and ADRB2 (Figure S3).",
        "results": "Immunohistochemistry results confirmed that COL5A1 and TOP2A were markedly overexpressed in LPS tissues relative to normal adipose tissues. In contrast, G0S2, GPD1, ADIPOQ, and ADRB2 showed significantly lower expression in LPS samples.",
        "results original text": "The expression of risk genes (COL5A1 and TOP2A) in LPS tissue was significantly higher than that in normal adipose tissue, while the opposite was true for the protective genes, G0S2, GPD1, ADIPOQ and ADRB2."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Kaplan-Meier Survival Analysis Based on Gene Expression Levels:\n   (1) Kaplan-Meier survival curves were plotted using distant recurrence-free survival (DRFS) data from the GSE30929 dataset to assess the prognostic values of the six signature genes.\n   (2) The analysis focused on risk genes (COL5A1 and TOP2A) and protective genes (ADRB2, GPD1, G0S2, and ADIPOQ) to evaluate their association with patient outcomes, emphasizing their potential role in prognosis.\n   (3) Statistical significance was determined using the log-rank test for survival curves, with p-values reported for each gene based on the analysis, indicating the strength of the association with survival outcomes.\n   (4) R software (version 4.0.4) was used for statistical analysis, utilizing the 'survival' package for Kaplan-Meier analysis, ensuring robust statistical evaluation.",
        "original text": "The prognostic values of these signature genes were estimated by plotting Kaplan\u2013Meier survival curves using DRFS data from GSE30929. As illustrated, patients with high expression of risk genes were significantly associated with worse DRFS (COL5A1, p = 0.0115; TOP2A, p < 0.0001, Figure 5A,B), indicating that they act as prognostic risk factors implicated in LPS progression.",
        "results": "Kaplan-Meier survival analysis showed that high expression of COL5A1 and TOP2A was significantly correlated with poor distant recurrence-free survival (DRFS) in LPS patients (COL5A1, p = 0.0115; TOP2A, p < 0.0001). Conversely, high expression of protective genes (ADRB2, GPD1, G0S2, and ADIPOQ) was associated with better DRFS outcomes.",
        "results original text": "Patients with high expression of risk genes were significantly associated with worse DRFS (COL5A1, p = 0.0115; TOP2A, p < 0.0001), indicating that they act as prognostic risk factors implicated in LPS progression."
    }
}{
    "Part 4": "Evaluation of the Prognostic Ability of Six-Gene Signature Indicates That It Is an Independent Predictor for LPS Prognosis",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Recurrence Analysis and Validation of the Risk Model:\n\u2460 Analyze the number of patients who suffered from LPS recurrence in high-risk and low-risk groups using the dataset GSE30929, which includes 140 LPS patients with survival data. \n\u2461 Create a heat map to visualize the expression levels of the four protective genes in low-risk patients who suffered from well-differentiated liposarcoma (WDLPS) and lower distant recurrence, while also showing the expression of two risk genes in high-risk patients who suffered from dedifferentiated liposarcoma (DDLPS) and higher distant recurrence.\n\u2462 Use GraphPad Prism software (version 9) for survival curve analysis, ensuring replicability by including specific parameters used for analysis, such as survival function estimation (Kaplan-Meier method) and p-value thresholds (p < 0.05). Include sample sizes for each group analyzed to provide context.",
        "original text": "As shown, the number of patients who suffered from LPS recurrence in the high-risk group was more than that in the low-risk group (Figure 6A), implying this risk model may be an indicator for LPS distant recurrence. As a heat map with clinicopathological characteristics illustrated, the expression of four protective genes was higher in low-risk patients who suffered from WDLPS and lower distant recurrence, while high-risk patients who suffered from DDLPS and higher distant recurrence exhibited higher expression of two risk genes (Figure 6B).",
        "results": "The analysis revealed that the high-risk group had a significantly higher number of patients experiencing distant recurrence compared to the low-risk group. The heat map illustrated higher expression of protective genes in low-risk patients with WDLPS and lower recurrence, whereas high-risk patients with DDLPS exhibited elevated expression of risk genes.",
        "results original text": "As shown, the number of patients who suffered from LPS recurrence in the high-risk group was more than that in the low-risk group (Figure 6A), implying this risk model may be an indicator for LPS distant recurrence."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. ROC Curve Analysis for Predictive Performance at 1-, 3-, and 5-Year DRFS:\n\u2460 Plot a survival curve by dividing patients into high- and low-risk groups to demonstrate the distant recurrence-free survival (DRFS) of low-risk patients being significantly better than that of high-risk patients, with a p-value < 0.0001. \n\u2461 Generate ROC curves to assess the predictive precision of the model for 1-, 3-, and 5-year DRFS using the dataset GSE30929, and report AUC values as 0.851, 0.850, and 0.788 respectively. \n\u2462 Specify the statistical software R (version 4.0.4) and the 'survival' package for ROC analysis, including functions such as `survfit()` for survival curves and `roc()` from the pROC package for ROC analysis, detailing any criteria for determining cut-off values.",
        "original text": "To further verify the prognostic ability of this risk model, a survival curve plotted by dividing patients into high- and low-risk groups revealed that DRFS of low-risk patients was significantly better than that of high-risk patients (p < 0.0001, Figure 6C), indicating the risk prediction ability of this model to distant recurrence. Subsequently, ROC curves were plotted to reveal the precision of this model in 1-, 3- and 5-year DRFS prediction for LPS (AUC values: 0.851, 0.850 and 0.788), implying the robust prognostic performance (Figure 6D).",
        "results": "The survival curve indicated that low-risk patients had significantly better DRFS compared to high-risk patients (p < 0.0001). The ROC analysis confirmed the model's predictive performance with AUC values of 0.851, 0.850, and 0.788 for 1-, 3-, and 5-year DRFS, respectively.",
        "results original text": "To further verify the prognostic ability of this risk model, a survival curve plotted by dividing patients into high- and low-risk groups revealed that DRFS of low-risk patients was significantly better than that of high-risk patients (p < 0.0001, Figure 6C)"
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Comparison of the Six-Gene Signature with Previous Prognostic Models:\n\u2460 Compare the six-gene model against previous studies on analyzing LPS gene profiles based on microarray data to highlight its improved performance. \n\u2461 Create a summary table to compare performance metrics, including C-index and AUC values, between the six-gene signature and previous prognostic models, thus providing a clear comparative analysis. Cite previous studies such as Liu et al. (2018), Gobble et al. (2011), and Iura et al. (2015) for reference, ensuring clarity in differences in methodology and outcomes.",
        "original text": "In contrast to previous studies on analyzing LPS gene profiles based on microarray data, we employed the more accurate Lasso algorithm to obtain this six-gene signature, which was further investigated, evaluated and validated to make our results more reliable and prove its robustness. Compared to previous studies [23\u201325], our model displayed more robust and beneficial performance: C-index in our risk model is much higher than that in Liu\u2019s model (0.779 vs. 0.711; 0.770 vs. 0.587); AUC value at 3-year of our risk model is much higher than that of Liu\u2019s model (0.850 vs. 0.772) (Table 1, Figure S11).",
        "results": "The six-gene signature demonstrated improved prognostic performance compared to earlier models, with a higher C-index and AUC values, thus establishing its efficacy as a more reliable prognostic tool for LPS.",
        "results original text": "Compared to previous studies [23\u201325], our model displayed more robust and beneficial performance: C-index in our risk model is much higher than that in Liu\u2019s model (0.779 vs. 0.711; 0.770 vs. 0.587); AUC value at 3-year of our risk model is much higher than that of Liu\u2019s model (0.850 vs. 0.772) (Table 1, Figure S11)."
    }
}{
    "Part 5": "Patients with Different Risk Scores Exhibit Distinct Molecular Subtypes and the Enriched Gene Sets",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Consensus Clustering Analysis of Patients Based on Expression Patterns of the Six Signature Genes\n1. Use the ConsensusClusterPlus package in R to classify LPS patients into two subgroups based on the expression patterns of the six signature genes derived from the GSE30929 dataset. \n2. Perform consensus clustering with a cumulative distribution function (CDF) approach, setting the maximum number of clusters to 6 and running 1000 iterations for stability assessment.\n3. Analyze the expression features of these genes between the two molecular subtypes; compare the expression levels of risk genes (COL5A1, TOP2A) and protective genes (GPD1, ADRB2, G0S2, ADIPOQ) in both clusters, using statistical tests to determine significance thresholds (p < 0.05).\n4. Plot a Kaplan-Meier survival curve to assess prognostic differences between the two molecular subtypes, indicating the survival outcomes for patients in each cluster, with p-values calculated to assess significance.",
        "original text": "Based on the expression pattern of the six signature genes, LPS patients with molecular heterogeneity were classified into two subgroups by consensus clustering (Figure S6A,B). The expression feature of these genes was investigated between two molecular subtypes; as a result, patients of cluster 1 presented significantly higher expression of risk genes but lower expression of protective genes compared to cluster 2 (Figure S6C). Furthermore, a survival curve demonstrated the significant prognostic differences between these two molecular subtypes, as illustrated; patients of cluster 1 underwent a poor prognosis, while cluster 2 received a beneficial prognosis (Figure S6D).",
        "results": "Patients classified into cluster 1 exhibited significantly higher expression levels of risk genes COL5A1 and TOP2A, while protective genes GPD1, ADRB2, G0S2, and ADIPOQ were significantly lower in this cluster. Additionally, Kaplan-Meier analysis indicated that cluster 1 had a significantly poorer prognosis compared to cluster 2, with p-values < 0.05.",
        "results original text": "Patients of cluster 1 presented significantly higher expression of risk genes but lower expression of protective genes compared to cluster 2. Furthermore, a survival curve demonstrated the significant prognostic differences between these two molecular subtypes, indicating that patients of cluster 1 underwent a poor prognosis, while cluster 2 received a beneficial prognosis."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. GSEA for Molecular Mechanisms and Pathways Enriched in High-Risk vs. Low-Risk Groups\n1. Conduct gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) using GSEA software version 4.2.3 to explore the molecular mechanisms affected by the prognostic gene signature in LPS patients from the GSE30929 dataset.\n2. Divide patients into high-risk and low-risk groups based on the risk scores calculated from the six-gene signature, using a median split for classification.\n3. Use the Molecular Signatures Database (MSigDB) to analyze the gene sets and identify pathways enriched in the high-risk group, focusing on cell cycle, DNA replication, and spliceosome pathways, and in the low-risk group, focusing on pathways associated with fatty acid metabolism and PPAR signaling. Record specific gene sets and their enrichment scores, ensuring that pathways with a false discovery rate (FDR) < 0.25 are highlighted for significance.",
